06432nam a22007575i 9780889209213DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20062005xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892092137 a10.51644/97808892092132doi  a(DE-B1597)667462  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR9180.1bA872 2005eb 7aLIT0040802bisacsh04a920/.0097122200aAuto/biography in Canada :bCritical Directions /ced. by Julie Rak. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©2005  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Studies ;v2500tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIntroduction— Widening the Field: Auto/biography Theory and Criticism in Canada -- tGenerations of the Holocaust in Canadian Auto/biography -- tThe Modern Hiawatha: Grey Owl’s Construction of His Aboriginal Self -- t“This is my memory, a fact”: The Many Mediations of Mothertalk: Life Stories of Mary Kiyoshi Kiyooka -- tAuto/biographical Jurisdictions: Collaboration, Self-Representation, and the Law in Stolen Life: The Journey of a Cree Woman -- tBiographical versus Biological Lives: Auto/biography and Non-Speaking Persons Labelled Intellectually Disabled -- tA Transfer Boy: About Himself -- tCreativity, Cultural Studies, and Potentially Fun Ways to Design and Produce Autobiographical Material from Subalterns’ Locations -- tCamp, Kitsch, Queer: Carole Pope and Toller Cranston Perform on the Page -- tWriting Lives in Death: Canadian Death Notices as Auto/biography -- t(Un)tying the Knot of Patriarchy: Agency and Subjectivity in the Autobiographical Writings of France Théoret and Nelly Arcan -- tAuto/Bio/Fiction in Migrant Women’s Writings in Quebec: Régine Robin’s La Québécoite and L’immense fatigue des pierres -- t“The ensign of the mop and the dustbin”: The Maternal and the Material in Autobiographical Writings by Laura Goodman Salverson and Nellie McClung -- tContributors -- tBooks in the Cultural Studies Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAuto/biography in Canada: Critical Directions widens the field of auto/biography studies with its sophisticated multidisciplinary perspectives on the theory, criticism, and practice of self, community, and representation. Rather than considering autobiography and biography as discrete genres with definable properties, and rather than focusing on critical approaches, the essays explore auto/biography as a discourse about identity and representation in the context of numerous disciplinary shifts. Auto/biography in Canada looks at how life narratives are made in Canada . Originating from literary studies, history, and social work, the essays in this collection cover topics that range from queer Canadian autobiography, autobiography and autism, and newspaper death notices as biography, to Canadian autobiography and the Holocaust, Grey Owl and authenticity, France Théoret and autofiction, and a new reading of Stolen Life, the collaborative text by Yvonne Johnson and Rudy Wiebe. Julie Rak’s useful “big picture” introduction traces the history of auto/biography studies in Canada. While the contributors chart disciplinary shifts taking place in auto/biography studies, their essays are also part of the ongoing scholarship that is remaking ways to understand Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutobiography. 0aBiography as a literary form. 0aBiography. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aLife Writing. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBraz, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChivers, Sally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEgan, Susanna, econtributo